<font color="#FF0000">VETS AARTIFICIAL LIMBS ARTICLE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 13 19:43:59 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Joe, I am going to leave most of what you said in &quot;A Thought of Two&quot; to the men on this site.  I am interested however in the article you mentioned that indicated young men were sitting in VA hospitals in the early 1970's waiting for up to three years for an artificial limb.   Something seems amiss here.  Men who lost a limb were not discharged from the service until they had been fitted for, given their prosthesis and taught how to use it.  The men stayed in the military awaiting a medical discharge.  Depending upon the severity of a man's injuries he could remain as a patient in a military  hospital for a couple of years.  Over the war era  military medicine changed how it handled amputee care.  When I first started in the hospital services the wound had to heal before the prosthesis process was started.  Later on, a temporary prosthesis was was used to get the man up and walking before the wound had healed and a permanent limb was issued after the stump shrank.   The military did not issue specialty prosthesis and it is possible that is what the article referenced.  An example of  specialty prosthesis include a leg which was capable of sustaining the jolt of landing on the ground after parachute jumping, or one designed for runners.  I know of no instances where the military sent a man home jumping on one leg while they waited three years for the VA to approve a limb.  
<p><code>--   (Class Lass) </code><p>


